Intervenes directly or through national or international authorities when free international circulation of the press is held up or hindered. Participates in educational activities in cooperation with 'Distripress Training Foundation'. Working Committees investigate trade topics and other matters of common interest. Organizes: Annual Congress; special regional conventions; seminars; trade fairs. Engages in improvement of overall environment for member companies and press distribution in general in the following areas: 
'Freedom of the Press' -In accordance with the UN Declaration of Human Rights and the UNESCO-Constitution, DISTRIPRESS engages itself worldwide for the free flow of information by word and image;
'Taxation' - based on the 1950 Agreement of UNESCO, intervenes against any kind of import duties on press products and against taxation on reading materials; 
'Marketing' - promotes exchange of information and experience about sales promotion, profitability of press products in retail trade, retail classification, sales analysis, data quality and sales information;
'Transportation' - maintains contact with all types of forwarders to secure speedy and efficient transportation on ground and in air, to facilitate customs clearance and to obtain adequate freight rates; 
'New Technologies' - fosters the exchange of information and experience on new methods of bundling, packing, processing unsold items, bar-coding etc; 
'European Union' - maintains contact with EU institutions to safeguard efficient press distribution systems that guarantee a wide variety of publications and a sufficient density of sales points throughout the European Union.

Intervenes directly or through national or international authorities when free international circulation of the press is held up or hindered. Participates in educational activities in cooperation with 'Distripress Training Foundation'. Working Committees investigate trade topics and other matters of common interest. Organizes: Annual Congress; special regional conventions; seminars; trade fairs. Engages in improvement of overall environment for member companies and press distribution in general in the following areas: 
'Freedom of the Press' - engages worldwide for free flow of information by word and image, in accordance with the UN Universal Declaration of Human Rights (UDHR, 1948) and with UNESCO Constitution; 
'Taxation' - based on the 1950 Agreement of UNESCO, Florence (Italy), intervenes against duties on press products and against taxation on reading materials; 
'Marketing' - promotes exchange of information and experience on sales promotion, profitability of press products in retail trade, retail classification, sales analysis, data quality and sales information;
'Transportation' - maintains contact with forwarders to secure speedy and efficient transportation by land or air, to facilitate customs clearance and to obtain adequate freight rates; 
'New Technologies' - fosters exchange of information and experience on new methods of bundling, packing, processing unsold items, bar-coding etc; 
'European Union' - maintains contact with EU institutions to safeguard efficient press distribution systems guaranteeing a wide variety of publications and a sufficient density of sales points throughout the European Union.

Organizes: national, regional and international conferences; seminars. Works through: 
Legal Practice Division (LPD), with over 50 specialist committees covering all areas of practice, those with common interests working together under Sections; 
Public and Professional Interest Division (PPID), covering activities of the legal profession, organized in "Constituents", and also the activities and interests of member organizations; 
Human Rights Institute (HRI), covering human rights and rule of law issues, including work with IBA Task Force on lnternational Terrorism.

Provides legal expertise at international, regional and national levels. 
'Eminent Jurist Panel on Terrorism, Counter-Terrorism and Human Rights' - examines the compatibility of laws, policies and practices justified expressly or implicitly as necessary to counter terrorism, with international human rights law and, where applicable, with international humanitarian law. 
Centre for the Independence of Judges and Lawyers (CIJL, no recent information) - works to promote and protect judicial and legal independence and impartiality. International Programmes (4): 
'Global Security and Rule of Law Programme' - mobilizes worldwide network, builds coalitions and steps up monitoring and interventions to persuade governments that counter-terrorism measures must respect the rule of law and human rights and humanitarian law;
'Judges and Lawyers Programme' - works to ensure that national justice systems are independent in law and practice, impartial and active in protecting human rights and freedoms and promote the rule of law; 
'International Economic Relations Programme' - addresses the legal accountability of increasingly powerful non-state economic actors when their conduct negatively affects human rights;
'International Law and Protection Programme' - takes a leading role in shaping and working for new global and regional international law when existing standards and mechanisms do not adequately protect, and for international law to be put into practice nationally. 
Regional Programmes (5): Middle East and North Africa; Latin America; Europe/North America and CIS; Asia-Pacific; Africa.

